Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and use `Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior` (toolbar back):

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () => await ConfirmDiscardAsync());
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async Task ConfirmDiscardAsync()
    {
        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

In your XAML, use `BackButtonBehavior` to replace the arrow with a text button that routes through the same confirmation logic:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then wire the command:

```csharp
public EditProductPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = this;
    CancelCommand = new Command(async () => await ConfirmDiscardAsync());
}

public ICommand CancelCommand { get; }
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles Android hardware/swipe back; return `true` to cancel.
- `BackButtonBehavior` with a `Command` intercepts the Shell toolbar back button — it replaces the default behavior entirely.
- Both paths funnel through `ConfirmDiscardAsync()` so the UX is consistent.
